Explore the gapminder object:

  1. Is it a data.frame, a matrix, a vector, a list?
class(gapminder)
## [1] "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"

Answer: The object of gapminder is a data.frame.

  1. What is its class?
class(gapminder)
## [1] "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"

Answer: The class of gapminder is a tbl_df.

Answer: str" function can get these facts, such as classes, objects, variables. Similarly, glimpse" can return the details of dataset while this method tries to show you as much data as possible. Another userful function is summary, which returns the values such as median, mean, max of the each variable. Functionls is also useful in returning the variables.

select(gapminder,year,pop, continent) %>%

Explore various plot types

Make a few plots, probably of the same variable you chose to characterize numerically. Lets see the relationship between life expectancy and continent

PLOT <- ggplot(gapminder, aes(x=continent, y=lifeExp))
  1. scatterplot
  PLOT + geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Scatter plot of Life Expectancy")

2. box plot

 PLOT + geom_boxplot() +
    ggtitle("Scatter plot of Life Expectancy")

3. violin plot

 PLOT + geom_violin() +
    ggtitle("Scatter plot of Life Expectancy")

4. overlap geom_violin and jitter plot

 PLOT + geom_violin() +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.1)

5. lets see the life expantancy in Americas with popolation more than 50 milion

 gapminder %>% 
  filter(continent == "Americas") %>% 
  filter(pop >= 50000000) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, group = 1)) + 
  facet_grid(~country) +
  geom_violin() +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.1)

6. lets compare lifeExp in Americas and in Asia with popolation more than 50 milion

 gapminder %>% 
  filter(continent == "Americas" | continent == "Asia") %>% 
  filter(pop >= 50000000) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, group = 1)) + 
  facet_grid(~continent) +
  geom_violin() +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.1)
